The first order of business is to provide an explicit expression for the
 divergent term.
 We can do this by considering a related and somewhat more interesting sum,
 the sum over second derivatives of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}$
\end_inset 

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset 

.
 Realizing that each 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}$
\end_inset 

 is parameterized by 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset 

, we can take its derivative: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
z'_{n+1}=\frac{d}{dc}z_{n+1}=2z'_{n}z_{n}+1\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

and 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
z''_{n+1}=\frac{d^{2}}{dc^{2}}z_{n+1}=2\left(z''_{n}z_{n}+\left(z'_{n}\right)^{2}\right)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{n}$
\end_inset 

, 
\begin_inset Formula $z'_{n}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z''_{n}$
\end_inset 

 are well defined for all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset 

 and finite 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset 

: they are entire functions, 'merely' polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset 

.
 Note that these polynomials never involve 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}$
\end_inset 

, the complex conjugate of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset 

, and thus all derivatives with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}$
\end_inset 

 are vanishing.
\layout Standard

Let us then define the sum 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{c}(t)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}z''_{n}\exp(-t^{2}n^{2})\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

Note that
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
P_{c}(t)=\frac{d^{2}}{dc^{2}}S_{c}(t)\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 holds for all positive 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset 

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{c}(t)$
\end_inset 

 also diverges as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/t$
\end_inset 

.
