\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\pi}$
\end_inset 

 merely left-right reflects the image.
\end_inset 


\layout Standard

The linearized coordinates can be immediately remapped to a circle by using
 the coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula \[
q=\rho e^{i\phi+i\pi}\]

\end_inset 

 where an extra factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset 

 is introduced to left-right reverse the image.
 This extra flip is needed to bring the coordinate system precisely into
 line with the Poincare punctured disk coordinates.
 The punctured disk coordinates are sometimes referred to as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

nome
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 coordinates of elliptic geometry.
 These are defined as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\omega_{2}/\omega_{1}$
\end_inset 

 be the so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

half-period ratio
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{2}$
\end_inset 

 are the periods of an elliptic function, such as the Weierstrass 
\begin_inset Formula $\wp$
\end_inset 

function.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

 is a coordinate on the upper half-plane, with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Im\tau>0$
\end_inset 

.
 The traditional 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

fundamental region
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 on the upper half-plane is defined as the region 
\begin_inset Formula $-1/2<\Re\tau\le1/2$
\end_inset 

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|\tau|>1$
\end_inset 

.
 This coordinate system on the upper half-plane can be mapped to the punctured
 disk as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
q=e^{i\pi\tau}\]

\end_inset 

 with the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset 

puncture
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset 

 referring to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset 

 never occurs for finite values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset 

.
 This mapping maps the upper half-plane to values of 
\begin_inset Formula $|q|<1$
\end_inset 

.
 The orientation of this mapping is specifically picked in order to be consisten
t with standard definitions of modular functions on the punctured disk.
 For example, the Euler phi-function, expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset 

 coordinates, is
